This is a known breaking change. .NET 10 MAUI enables **edge-to-edge** display by default on Android, and `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` (deprecated since Android 11) no longer adjusts your layout. You need to react to **IME window insets** instead.

### The fix

**1. Keep `adjustResize` in your manifest** (`Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`):

```xml
<activity android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" ... />
```

This still tells the system the app *wants* to resize — but with edge-to-edge, **you** are responsible for consuming the insets.

**2. Add an inset listener in platform code.** Create a helper in `Platforms/Android/`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using AndroidX.Core.Graphics;

public static class KeyboardInsetHelper
{
    public static void Apply(View rootView)
    {
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new InsetListener());
    }

    private class InsetListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use whichever is taller — keyboard or nav bar
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);

            view.SetPadding(
                view.PaddingLeft,
                view.PaddingTop,
                view.PaddingRight,
                bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Wire it up in `MainActivity.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
    KeyboardInsetHelper.Apply(Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!);
}
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 (old model) | .NET 10 (edge-to-edge) |
|---|---|
| System auto-shrinks the window | App draws behind system bars & keyboard |
| `Resize` handled it for you | You consume `Ime()` insets to add padding |

The `Ime()` inset type gives you the **exact keyboard height** in pixels. When the keyboard is hidden, `imeInsets.Bottom` is `0` and you fall back to the navigation-bar inset so your input bar sits just above the gesture bar.

### Alternative: opt out of edge-to-edge (quick workaround)

If you want the old behavior back temporarily, you can disable edge-to-edge in `OnCreate` **before** `base.OnCreate`:

```csharp
// Not recommended long-term — edge-to-edge is the Android default going forward
AndroidX.Activity.EdgeToEdge.Disable(this);
```

The inset-listener approach is the forward-compatible solution.
